 By Arshad Mahmud Washington, July 4 (bdnews24.com)When an official study recently reported a sudden rise in teen pregnancy in the United States, policy makers and experts began scratching their heads: what to do now and how to tackle the problem? The report made it clear that efforts to get young people to either abstain from sex or use birth control are falling short. So it is not surprising to see that different organisations and institutions are trying different approaches aimed at weaning the teenage girls away from engaging in unprotected sex and get them through high school without getting pregnant. Among different approaches that are being tried, one program is getting a lot of media attention: The University of North Carolina in Greensboro has offered the girls a simple bargain under a new program called "College Bound Sisters" in which they are paid a dollar for every day they don't get pregnant. The program, funded through a state grant and private donations, is open only to girls aged 12-18, who have an older sister who had a baby as a teen. To qualify for the program, participants have to express interest in attending college, can never have been pregnant themselves and are required to attend an hour-and-a-half-long weekly meeting at the university (so they have to live nearby). And they don't get to spend the money right away; it's socked away and disbursed upon the girls' enrolling in a college. It is, of course, too early to predict the program's success. But already some people have raised objections, saying offering incentives for behaving well isn't appropriate; some even likened it to offering kids cash for not smoking pot. No wonder the policy makers are faced with a moral dilemma. They are asking whether it's an appropriate way to tackle the teenage pregnancy problem. Some experts are asking: Is this dollar-a-day idea a good one that perhaps deserves to be implemented more broadly, or is it just a br
